  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries around the world. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key aspects of AML regulations include:\n\n1. Requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Monitor and report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\n2. Major legislative frameworks include:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (United States)\n- European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) international standards\n\n3. These regulations cover various financial sectors:\n- Banks\n- Credit unions\n- Investment firms\n- Money transfer services\n- Cryptocurrency exchanges\n\n4. Penalties for non-compliance can include:\n- Significant financial fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of business licenses\n\nThe primary goal of AML regulations is to detect and prevent financial crimes like money laundering, terrorist financing, and other illegal financial activities.",
